      "orig": "The term AIRcanbeparsedin two differentways. Forlinear systems the two interpretationsareidentical. We introduced the AIRabove as the analytic\"impulse response,\"a complex function whose real part is the impulse response.This interpretation follows (roughly) alyticimpulse\"response,the(complex) response of a system to a complex impulse,namely,\u25b3(t).This interpretation corresponds to Eq.(1b).In this light,\u25b3(t) appears as the AIR of an ideal system. This is to say, the function\u25b3(t)plays a dual role.From oneperspective it is the toolwe use to calculate theAIRforagiven system.But at the same time,we may regard it as the data itself, the response of a system with everywhereflat frequency response.",
      "text": "The term AIRcanbeparsedin two differentways. Forlinear systems the two interpretationsareidentical. We introduced the AIRabove as the analytic\"impulse response,\"a complex function whose real part is the impulse response.This interpretation follows (roughly) alyticimpulse\"response,the(complex) response of a system to a complex impulse,namely,\u25b3(t).This interpretation corresponds to Eq.(1b).In this light,\u25b3(t) appears as the AIR of an ideal system. This is to say, the function\u25b3(t)plays a dual role.From oneperspective it is the toolwe use to calculate theAIRforagiven system.But at the same time,we may regard it as the data itself, the response of a system with everywhereflat frequency response."
